                  how long it takes to read your text.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Highlight any portion of the text to see
                  <strong>selection-only statistics</strong>.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>What this text counter measures</h2>
              <h3>1. Word count</h3>
              <p>
                A word is defined as any sequence of non-whitespace characters
                separated by spaces, tabs, or line breaks. Multiple spaces are
                treated as a single separator, so formatting won’t distort your
                count.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Word counting logic (simplified):
                </p>
                <pre class="text-xs whitespace-pre-wrap"><code>words = text
  .trim()
  .split(/\s+/)          // split on any whitespace
  .filter(token =&gt; token.length &gt; 0)
  .length</code></pre>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Character count (with and without spaces)</h3>
              <p>
                Many platforms (social networks, SMS, form fields) limit
                characters rather than words. This tool shows:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Characters (with spaces):</strong> every visible
                  character, including spaces and line breaks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Characters (no spaces):</strong> all characters except
                  regular spaces, tabs, and line breaks.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Sentences, paragraphs, and lines</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sentences</strong> are detected using punctuation such
                  as <code>.</code>, <code>!</code>, or <code>?</code> followed
                  by a space or line break.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Paragraphs</strong> are blocks of text separated by
                  one or more blank lines.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Lines</strong> are counted purely by line breaks
                  (useful for code, lists, or poetry).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Average word length</h3>
              <p>Average word length is calculated as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1"><strong>Average word length</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Avg word length} = \frac{\text{Characters without
                  spaces}}{\text{Number of words}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This can help you gauge readability: shorter average words
                usually mean simpler, more accessible text.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Reading time estimate</h3>
              <p>
                Reading time is estimated from the word count using a
                configurable reading speed:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1"><strong>Reading time</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Minutes} = \frac{\text{Word count}}{\text{Words per
                  minute (WPM)}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                You can choose between
                <strong>150, 200, or 250 words per minute</strong> to match
                slow, average, or fast readers. The result is displayed in
                minutes and seconds for clarity.
              </p>

              <h2>Common use cases</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Students:</strong> Check essay length against
                  assignment requirements.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Authors &amp; bloggers:</strong> Keep articles within
                  target word ranges.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Social media managers:</strong> Stay under character
                  limits for posts and ads.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Developers:</strong> Measure string lengths for UI
                  constraints or database fields.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Translators &amp; editors:</strong> Compare source and
                  target text lengths.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Accuracy notes & limitations</h2>
              <p>
                This tool aims to match how most editors and platforms count
                words and characters, but minor differences can occur because:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Different apps treat hyphenated words or emojis differently.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Some platforms normalize line breaks or special whitespace
                  characters.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Sentence detection is heuristic and may not handle every edge
                  case in complex technical or legal text.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For critical submissions (e.g., journal articles or exam
                essays), always double-check with the platform’s own counter if
                available.
              </p>

              <h2>Privacy: your text stays in your browser</h2>
              <p>
                The text counter runs entirely in JavaScript on your device.
                Your content is <strong>not uploaded</strong> or stored on a
                server by this tool, making it safe for drafts, confidential
                notes, and work documents.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Can I count only part of the text?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Select any portion of the text in the box. The “Selection
                statistics” panel will show word, character, sentence counts,
                and reading time for the highlighted part only.
              </p>

              <h3>Does it support non‑Latin languages?</h3>
              <p>
                The counter works with any Unicode text. For languages that
                don’t use spaces between words (such as Chinese or Japanese),
                the word count may be less meaningful, but character counts
                remain accurate.
              </p>
